            <marginalia hand="Italian">
                <language ident="LA">
                    <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                        <marginalia_text> Romae [-] Athenaru[m] populares humores, regias mundi sententias, regulasq[ue] corrupere
                            <!-- Piece of page missing. -->
                        </marginalia_text>
                        <location name="Rome"/>
                        <location name="Athens"/>
                    </position>
                </language>
                <translation>
                    The popular humors of Rome [-] of Athens corrupted the regal sentiments of the world and its models.
                </translation>
            </marginalia>
            
            <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="Garbato.">
                <language ident="IT">
                    <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                        <marginalia_text>ridicolo</marginalia_text>
                    </position>
                </language>
                <translation>
                    Ridiculous.
                </translation>
            </marginalia>	
            
            <marginalia hand="Italian">
                <language ident="LA">
                    <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="270">
                        <marginalia_text> = Canonista: pragmatista. Ex occulto; stratagematista; apophthegmatista.
                            Emblematista: Epigrammatista.
                        </marginalia_text>
                    </position>
                </language>
                <translation>
                    Canonist: pragmatist. In secret; strategist; aphorist. Emblemist: epigrammatist.
                </translation>
            </marginalia>
            
            <marginalia hand="Italian">
                <language ident="LA">
                    <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                         <marginalia_text> 
                               Ante omnes auctores, politicus Bodini:  
		                 </marginalia_text>
                           <person name="Jean Bodin"/>
                           <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="politicus Bodini" />
		</position>
		<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">	
		      <marginalia_text>
			    Jureconsult[u]s Vigelij: pragmaticus Speculatoris:
		      </marginalia_text>
		      <person name="Nikolaus Vigel" />
		      <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Jureconsult[i]s Vigelij: pragmaticus speculatoris" /> 
		</position>
		<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
		    <marginalia_text>
		          strategematicus Gandini: apophthegmaticus Zuingeri. Prudententiss[imi] 
		     </marginalia_text>
		      <person name="Marcantonio Gandino" />
              <person name="Theodor Zwinger" />	
		      <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="strategematicus Gandini: apophthegmaticus Zuingeri" />
		</position>
                      <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                            <marginalia_text>
                                auctores, maximique necessarij.
                            </marginalia_text>
                    </position>
                </language>
                <translation>
                    Before all authors, the politician of Bodin: the lawyer of Vigel: the pragmatist of the Speculator: the strategist of Gandino: the aphorist of Zwinger. The most prudent and epecially necessary authors. 
                </translation>
            </marginalia>
            
			<marginalia hand="Italian">
				<language ident="LA">
					<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
						<marginalia_text>s[upr]a</marginalia_text>
					</position>
				</language>
			    <translation>
			        [See] above.
			    </translation>
			</marginalia>
			
            <marginalia hand="Italian">
                <language ident="LA">
                    <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                             <marginalia_text>
                                 Classicis auctoribus addo Bartasium, ob divinum furore[m]: Rabelaesiu[m],
                             </marginalia_text>
		      <person name="Guillaume Du Bartas" />
                            <person name="Francois Rabelais" />
                    </position>
                    <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                            <marginalia_text>
                                ob humanu[m]: Chauceru[m], ob mixtu[m].
                            </marginalia_text>
                            <person name="Geoffrey Chaucer" />
                    </position>	
                </language>
                <translation>
                    To the classical authors I add Barthas, for his divine fury: Rabelais for his human fury: Chaucer, for a mixture. 
                </translation>
            </marginalia>
            
            <marginalia hand="Italian">
                <language ident="IT">
                    <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                        <marginalia_text>ridicolo.</marginalia_text> 
                    </position> 
                </language>
                <translation>
                    ridiculous.
                </translation>
            </marginalia>
            
            <marginalia hand="Italian">
                <language ident="LA">
                    <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                        <marginalia_text> 
                            ) Malo Chaucerum, qua[m] Petrarcha[m]; Boccatium, aut Ariostum. Rabelaesium, quam Aretinum.
                        </marginalia_text>
                        <person name="Petrarch" />
                        <person name="Francois Rabelais" />	
                        <person name="Pietro Aretino" />
                        <person name="Ludovico Ariosto" />	
                        <person name="Geoffrey Chaucer" />
                        <person name="Giovanni Boccaccio" />				
                    </position>
                </language>
                <translation>
                    I prefer Chaucer rather than Petrarch; Boccaccio, or else Ariosto. Rabelais, rather than Aretino.
                </translation>
            </marginalia>
        
            
